@yatli In firefox it is narrow black heart. In chromium (desktop and mobile) it is a narrow red heart. The modifier is always needed to make it double width.

> On Windows10, even without the selector, 0x2764 should be double-width.

What does this even mean?  Terminal programs can run on one platform and be displayed on another over ssh, so they have to follow some kind of standard. Arbitrarily changing unicode semantics on each platform doesn't sound very useful.

> I was not complaining, just stating a fact. Sorry if it came off poorly. I just want to help, but I'm feeling like you're shutting me down just for posting here and asking about ideas for a fix.

![first-time-james-franco](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/45028928/e815fd9e-0c9e-4099-afd9-379fe66f15ce)

@bonsairobo Don't take it personally, this is just how they choose to run their issues I guess. I've gone through the same thing, and have seen it happen more than once here in `neovim/issues`. Maybe they're just understaffed or something (don't have enough contributors/moderators/maintainers etc.). Regardless, there's got to be a better, more professional and friendly way to handle such user inquiries than the current strict and defensive/standoffish posture. Just my 2 cents.
